# üöÄSupport multiple Angular apps running in one window with ViewEncapsulation.Emulated.


### Description
I am working on a setup that will have multiple Angular apps (with separate instances of Angular itself) rendering into the same document. `_nghost-c*` and `_ngcontent-c*` attributes generated by Angular's `emulated` view encapsulation rely on an internal auto-incremented counter:

https://github.com/angular/angular/blob/885f1af509eb7d9ee049349a2fe5565282fbfefb/packages/core/src/view/util.ts#L59-L77

CSS rules produced by them can easily result in conflicts when there are multiple Angular apps running in that page.

For example, the following component:

```javascript
@Component({
selector: 'my-app',
styles: [`
  :host {
    display: block;
    border: 1px solid black;
  }
  div {
    color: blue;
  }
`],
})
class MyApp {
}
```

will generate

```html
<style>
[_nghost-c5] {
  display: block;
  border: 1px solid black;
}
div[_ngcontent-c5] {
  color: blue;
}
</style>
```

Since each Angular instance has its own copy of the auto-incremented ID, these rules will also unintentionally apply to components with the same generated ID rendered by the another instance of Angular running in the same window. 

### Describe the solution you'd like
Use a globally unique component ID.
Alternatively, allow the component ID generator function to be configurable as an injection token.

### Describe alternatives you've considered
The solution has to work for an existing large-scale Angular application, so migrating everything away from the default view encapsulation is a non-starter.

‚Ä¶ll `ng doc` with Windows.

It's just a proposal,  we can also use `wait: true` for the three platform MacOS, Windows and Linux like this:

```js
        let chromeName;
        if (process.platform === 'darwin') {
          chromeName = 'google chrome';
        } else if (process.platform === 'win32') {
          chromeName = 'chrome';
        } else if (process.platform === 'linux') {
          chromeName = 'google-chrome';
        }

        return opn(searchUrl, {
          app: chromeName,
          wait: true,
        });

```

We may also pass the browser as option.


